Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: While the original SPIRSA framework offers a compelling approach by combining representational similarity metrics with semantic perturbations, it primarily focuses on *detecting* overfitting and bias through post-hoc analysis. My motivation is to shift from passive diagnosis to active intervention—transforming detection into correction. Drawing inspiration from Paper 2 (MISO), which uses semantically meaningful oversampling to re-embed difficult minority samples, I propose integrating the diagnostic power of intra-layer self-similarity and inter-layer linear CKA not just as evaluation tools, but as *guidance signals for targeted representation refinement*. The key insight is that layers exhibiting high instability (measured via perturbation-induced drops in CKA and self-similarity) are not merely indicators of overfitting—they can serve as "attention maps" for where and how to apply corrective transformations. By identifying these fragile layers and linking them to specific minority name representations, we can design a feedback loop that generates disentangled, robust embeddings for underrepresented names using mutual information constraints and adversarial reconstruction. This moves beyond auditing toward *self-correcting models*, aligning with real-world needs in regulated AI applications where fairness must be both measurable and improvable. Unlike prior work, this idea fuses three previously separate paradigms: (1) dynamic representational stability analysis, (2) semantic oversampling for imbalanced data, and (3) latent structure-guided embedding correction—all orchestrated through layer-wise sensitivity signals. It introduces a closed-loop framework where detection directly informs debiasing, making it more actionable than static diagnostics.

